title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 700 Police Sniper .308
postcontent:
Police Sniper 26" heavy barrel, this is the older model Police Sniper which means all steel hardware (no crappy plastic trigger guard) and nicely blued finish, not the current matte black. Action is sitting in a current Remington AAC Hogue overmolded stock with Harris bipod, though the original (and insanely heavy) walnut stock with old style Anschutz forend rail is available for you retro rifle hounds. Bolt was polished and jeweled, action blueprinted, and trigger work done, though in the old style of doing things this means there is no safety lever. God knows why they used to do that, or for that matter why some people still do that, but they do. Its easy enough to add the safety lever back on I guess, but far better to just put in a more modern aftermarket trigger group with proper external adjustments. Base and rings are installed, and an older style scope is included simply because its already there. Works well enough, but the scope really needs replacing with a proper FFP mil-dot scope with turrets to bring it up to modern standards of a tactical rifle.
 Both trigger and scope function as well as they ever did I guess, they put the all bullets in the same hole in the target just fine, they are just of rudimentary design by modern technical standards. Basically I am selling this as a rifle stock and a nicely tuned barreled action for someone to start a project, so no complaints that the scope and trigger are antique pieces of crap! 

  All in all, a good starter long range rifle as it sits, and a good accurate and consistent platform with all the important work already done to build up a very nice rifle from in the future by upgrading those two parts.

title: Want To Buy:  Colt Cobra .32 (sold in Alabama)
postcontent:
I am trying to recover a blued Colt Cobra .32 in .32 Colt caliber with wood grips, serial number 1403X (1952 production, I believe). If anyone reading this happens to be or know its current owner or have a clue as to its whereabouts, please let me know as I would be willing and eager to pay a generous premium over whatever was paid for it for its return. I would also happily buy another Colt of equal or greater value of the owners choosing to trade.

The revolver once belonged to the father of a close friend of mine--it was his off-duty weapon in the 50s. He passed it down to my friend who passed it down to his own son...who pawned it and everything else not nailed down to feed his heroin addiction. My friend is kind of torn up over the whole deal. I'm hoping to ease his mind in at least some small way by recovering his heirloom.

Please note, the gun was NOT STOLEN. Its current owner, I'm sure, has every right to keep it. It was pawned as legitimately as possible as far as the law is concerned, and the pawn shop sold it just as legitimately. I would simply like to reaquire it the same way. It was sold at a pawnshop in Alabama. It's been several months now, so god knows where it could have gotten to in the mean time.

Thanks to anyone who takes the time to read this, and double thanks for anyone who considers this ad the next time they happen across a Cobra that matches this description.

title: Want To Buy:  Colt 1911s to fill out my collection
postcontent:
Looking for a few specific Colts to round out my collection. These are specific models, some quite colectable, and some less so. If you are familiar with colt 1911s you will know these.

1. Gold Cup Commander in either blue or stainless. Prefer first issue, but will consider later issue if pistol has all features of first issue. No lightweight pistols. Must have original box and paperwork. Prefer in unfired condition, but not a deal breaker.

2. Series 70 Combat Government. Blued. These were produced toward the end of 70 Series production, and will have a 70B prefixed serial number. Prefer unfired, but lightly used and well maintained is OK. Original box and paperwork is a plus.

3. Series 80 enhanced Combat Commander. Prefer stainless, but will consider blued version. Must have all enhancements (Flat top slide, angled cocking serrations, undercut trigger guard, duck bill grip safety, deluxe hammer, etc.). No lightweights. This need not be a safe queen, but should be priced commensurate with condition. As always, original box and paperwork will add value.

Willing to spend up to listed amount, or perhaps a bit more for the right pistol. Please respond with a brief description of condition, and asking price. I have cash in hand for pistols meeting the above criteria, and am a serious buyer. Please be a serious seller.

This is considered to be one of the best CCW revolvers ever made, and the only reason I’m considering parting with it is because I am consolidating calibers and funding another purchase.

This is a 4th Generation Charter Arms “PUG” from the plant in Shelton, Connecticut, and is the best model they’ve ever designed.  The alloy frame keeps it light, the 2" barrel keeps it pocketable, and the .44 Special cartridge packs the punch of a .45 ACP with far less recoil than a .357 Magnum.  Magnum recoil is very sharp and snappy, whereas the .44 Special is more like a firm push.  This is the best big bore caliber for short barrels or recoil sensitive shooters, and is a very accurate round.

The PUG has a stainless finish, practical sights, and a snag-free DAO hammer.  Lockup is very tight and revolver has a VERY low round count.  It is practically in like new condition.

This comes with the stock rubber finger-groove grips.  They are offering a new style of rubber grip now, Hogue also offers one, and older wood grips from the Bulldog and Undercover will also fit so there are plenty of options available if you want to swap it out.

Speaker Mike Madigan has called for two public hearings for Illinois residents to voice their support or opposition to proposed Right to Carry legislation.

2. Enter "NA" for "persons, groups, firms represented". 

3. Position. You will need to enter each subject matter issue you wish to support or oppose. Click on the circle beside your choice of position. (DO NOT USE THE ARROW KEYS, doing so will change your vote - use the scroll bar to navigate around the page).

Shall issue license carry - proponent

Registration of firearm/magazines - opponent 
Banning private sales/transfers of firearms - opponent 
One gun a month - opponent 
Report lost or stolen firearm - opponent 

5. Testimony - check "record of appearance" if you are not giving oral or written testimony. 

6. Please submit only one slip per person.

For sale is my Volunteer Enterprises Commando MKIII .45ACP carbine, a semi-auto rifle styled after an Auto Ordinance Tommy Gun. This gun is a late model, manufactured in 1975, making it one of the highest-quality and most reliable Commandos out there. It uses 30-round M3 Grease Gun mags, which are still cheap and plentiful on GunBroker - much cheaper than actual Thompson 20-round stick mags. The receiver, 16-inch barrel, compensator, and magazine have been recently refinished in DuPont Teflon black at a cost of $250, and look excellent. It has been thoroughly cleaned and lubed, and only 5 rounds have been fired since the refinish to ensure proper function. 

I am also including a spare lower receiver, which I had planned to refinish and convert to use a genuine Thompson wooden handgrip and trigger, as well as the mechanism required to convert the stock to a push-button release, again emulating a genuine Thompson. The wooden buttstock can be easily removed with two screws, and the gun is quite fun to shoot without the stock. I am also including a spare ejector, ejector pin, and ejector spring, good spare parts to have around. It has the rock-solid feel and fun of a Thompson to shoot, at a significantly lower cost. 

33rd-edition of the Blue Book of Gun Values places the value of this rifle in good condition at $825, which does not include the spare parts.
